China Stocks: Vanke, Agricultural Bank, Angang Steel, Insigma

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-04-28T07:47:56Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-28/china-stocks-petrochina-sinopec-angang-steel-zijin-mining.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and share prices are as of the 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, fell 1.3 percent to 2,887.04. The  CSI
300 Index (SHSZ300)  dropped 1.5 percent to 3,161.78.  Developers: China Vanke Co. (000002 CH), the nation’s
largest developer by market value, retreated 1.1 percent to 8.31
yuan. Poly Real Estate Group Co. (600048 CH), the second
largest, slid 2.8 percent to 12.91 yuan.  Real estate stocks dropped on concern higher borrowing
costs may curb spending. China may raise  interest rates  early
next month, with the “most likely” timing being May 2,
following the May 1 holiday, Credit Suisse Group AG said in a
report today. The central government may increase measures to
cool the  property market  by extending restrictions on house
purchases, or by requiring local governments to set stricter
targets for controlling  home prices , analysts led by  Li Huiyong 
at Shenyin & Wanguo Securities wrote in a report today.  Agricultural Bank of China Ltd. (601288)  (601288 CH), the nation’s
largest lender by customers, jumped 2.1 percent to 2.96 yuan,
its biggest gain since April 14. The company’s first-quarter
profit rose 36 percent to the highest in more than a year as
profitability of loans and fee income increased, according to a
statement to the Hong Kong stock exchange yesterday.  Angang Steel Co. (000898 CH) lost 2.4 percent to 7.77 yuan,
the lowest close since Feb. 25. The steelmaker’s first-quarter
profit tumbled 94 percent from a year earlier to 71 million yuan
($11 million), according to a statement to the Shenzhen Stock
Exchange yesterday.  China Shipping Container Lines Co. (601866 CH) plunged 6.6
percent to 4.13 yuan, the largest decline since Nov. 12. The
company reported a first-quarter net loss of 146.1 million yuan,
according to a statement to the stock exchange yesterday.  Insigma Technology Co. (600797 CH), a computer networking
equipment maker, surged 6.7 percent to 7.18 yuan. The company’s
first-quarter net income rose six-fold to 79.9 million yuan,
according to a statement to the exchange yesterday.  --Irene Shen, Liza Lin. Editor: Allen Wan  To contact Bloomberg News staff for this story:
